// When a function calls itself until a specified condition is met.
int count = 0;
void f(){
  if(count == 4){
    return;
    }
  Syste.out.println(count);
  count++;
  f();
  }
// When we call this function in the main method. 
// The function gets executed and the value of count will be printed until it reaches the base case.
// Until the base case is reached, the function remain waiting in the stack memory. 
// When the last function call is finished, then it returns to the function that called itself. 
// in this way the function returns one by one and the stack memory is freed. 
// And at last the other lines of codes are executed and process is finished.
